{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504744"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:19:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:19:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2363"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2363"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0,0.09,0.56,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109069"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2363"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91436"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1226"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1573"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8874"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11832"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40672"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42476"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109069"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man is brought to a GP by his father. His father says he and other family members have observed that his son has always tried to distance himself from other people with no friends and no romantic partners. He says that his son has always been like this throughout his life. Yesterday, his son refused to join a party that his father was hosting. His father states \u201cThat was the last straw and I had to get him checked to see why he avoids meeting new people\u201d. Upon asking his son separately, he reports he dislikes how people get too personal and that he is content with how things are in his life. Further assessment interviews with the patient failed to reveal any symptoms of anxiety associated with being in the presence of others or any odd or unusual thoughts or experiences. Academically, he is a bright student. His appetite and sleep are normal and he has no suicidal ideations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn mental state examination, he appeared well dressed without tattoos. He had a flat affect. His speech was the appropriate rate and volume and his answers were brief but appropriate without tangentiality.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following diagnoses would be most consistent with this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Avoidant personality disorder","Generalised anxiety disorder","Autistic spectrum disorder","Schizoid personality disorder","Social anxiety disorder"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a long history of avoiding social activities and his presentation is most consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Eschizoid personality disorder\u003C/strong\u003E (SPD). SPD is a Cluster A personality disorder characterised by a preference to avoid social activities. Patients tend to like loneliness and avoid situations where they have to interact with other people. These patients typically stay in their rooms or houses and avoid meeting new people or developing relationships.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eavoidant personality disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is similar to a schizoid personality disorder since both of these disorders are characterised by patients avoiding social activities. However, patients with \u003Cstrong\u003Eavoidant personality disorder\u003C/strong\u003E avoid people NOT because they want to, but because they do not have self-confidence and are afraid of criticism. On the other hand, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eschizoid personality disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by avoiding social activities just because the patient likes to be alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneralised anxiety disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is diagnosed if the patient has multiple excessive worries for \u22656 months. It may also be associated with fatigue, headaches, irritability, and muscle tension. This patient does not have a history of worrying about multiple issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutistic spectrum disorder \u003C/strong\u003Eis a diagnostic label that incorporates older diagnoses of autism, Asperger\u0027s disorder and pervasive developmental disorder. Symptoms become apparent during early development and are lifelong, including deficits in social communication and interaction as well as restricted, repetitive patterns of behaviour. While this patient has long standing relationship deficits and possibly an insistence on sameness there is insufficient information about repetitive behaviours, interests, sensory reactivity and his style of verbal and non verbal communication to make the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESocial anxiety disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by excessive worry for \u22656 months about one or more social circumstances. Patients are afraid of criticism and humiliation that leads to significant distress. These patients tend to avoid social activities because of intense distress. This patient does not report any distress regarding social activities. He simply prefers to be alone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Schizoid personality disorder is a Cluster A personality disorder characterised by a preference to avoid social activities."],"references":["Esterberg M, Goulding S, Walker E. Cluster A Personality Disorders: Schizotypal, Schizoid and Paranoid Personality Disorders in Childhood and Adolescence. Journal of Psychopathology and Behavioral Assessment. 2010;32(4):515-528. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2992453/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91436"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2363"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91436"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T20:23:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T20:24:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2363"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109069"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group